Shopify-Amazon Follow-Up
------------------------

I received a very interesting bit of feedback from a reader arguing that ty=
ing Amazon Pay to Buy with Prime wasn=E2=80=99t really that important to Am=
azon strategically; rather, by controlling payments Amazon could better pro=
tect the brand value of Prime. For example, if there were some sort of snaf=
u, Amazon could easily issue a refund; that would be much more difficult to=
 do if Buy with Prime were allowed to work with a different payment provide=
r.

That, though, actually makes me more optimistic about a potential Amazon-Sh=
opify agreement: Shopify could provide various guarantees to Amazon around =
things like refunds and dispute resolutions, and make Amazon whole immediat=
ely without the need for Amazon to offer a de facto loan to a merchant on w=
hose behalf they issued a refund; on the merchant side Shopify could also t=
ake on the burden of merchant verification and validation, perhaps by limit=
ing Buy with Prime to one of its premium service tiers (which would also ha=
ve the benefit of driving high margin subscription revenue for Shopify). Al=
l of this is very much in the spirit of the platform Shopify wants to be: a=
 common interface between different parts of the value chain.

Amazon and Pinterest
--------------------

From TechCrunch ( https://techcrunch.com/2023/04/27/pinterest-announces-mul=
ti-year-ads-partnership-with-amazon/ ) :

Pinterest today announced a multiyear strategic ad partnership with Amazon =
aimed at bringing more brands and relevant products to its platform. The ne=
w deal will make the e-commerce giant Pinterest=E2=80=99s first partner on =
third-party ads, the company said in a blog post ( https://newsroom.pintere=
st.com/en/post/pinterest-announces-partnership-with-amazon-to-bring-third-p=
arty-ad-demand-to-the-platform ) shared alongside its first-quarter earning=
s beat=E2=80=A6

While Pinterest has for years worked to connect product inspiration to purc=
hases, the Amazon ads partnership could potentially offer consumers a more =
seamless buying experience. Unlike on some e-commerce websites, Amazon shop=
pers may not have to fiddle with filling out forms, as most have their paym=
ent information already on file with the company, leading to faster checkou=
ts. When users click on an Amazon ad on Pinterest, they=E2=80=99ll be taken=
 directly to Amazon to make the purchase, Pinterest says.

This is a deal that simultaneously makes a lot of sense for Pinterest, even=
 as it is a pretty bearish indicator for the company=E2=80=99s long-term pr=
ospects.

There are, broadly speaking, two important elements of digital advertising.=
 The first is accurately targeting users with ads that are relevant to them=
. The best way to do this is search advertising, like Google or Amazon. The=
 most valuable way to do this is knowing enough about the customer to show =
them ads they will probably be interested in; this is what Meta excels at, =
and the reason it is so valuable is because while search ads depend on the =
user already knowing what they are looking for, targeted ads of the Meta va=
riety expose the user to products they didn=E2=80=99t know existed, or didn=
=E2=80=99t know that they might want. The third way to do this is through c=
ontextual advertising: showing the user products that are similar to whatev=
er they are looking at currently.

The second element of digital advertising is tracking conversions: did the =
user actually buy the product in the ad that they saw? This was the part of=
 digital advertising that was most hurt by Apple=E2=80=99s App Tracking Tra=
nsparency initiative: it used to be that an advertising platform like Meta =
would place a pixel on an advertiser=E2=80=99s website, or an SDK in their =
app, and be able to perfectly measure the extent to which a particular ad l=
ed to a conversion (and how much that conversion ended up being worth in th=
e long run). In this world advertising was a determinative exercise: everyt=
hing could be measured, which meant that companies like Meta could basicall=
y sell growth to any company willing to pay.

In the post-ATT world you can still measure conversions, as long as they ha=
ppen on your platform (more on this in a moment); absent that, though, the =
best ad platforms can offer is probabilistic measurement: they don=E2=80=99=
t know for sure which ad converted, but they have a pretty good idea, at le=
ast in theory. To the extent that Meta has cracked the ATT code ( https://s=
tratechery.com/2023/facebook-earnings-generative-ai-and-messaging-monetizat=
ion-open-source-and-ai/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0=
ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS=
5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJlbnQiOnsidXJpIjpbImh0dHBzOi8vc3RyYXRlY2hlcnkuY29tL=
zIwMjMvZmFjZWJvb2stZWFybmluZ3MtZ2VuZXJhdGl2ZS1haS1hbmQtbWVzc2FnaW5nLW1vbmV0=
aXphdGlvbi1vcGVuLXNvdXJjZS1hbmQtYWkvIl19LCJleHAiOjE2ODYyMzQ0OTksImlhdCI6MTY=
4MzY0MjQ5OSwiaXNzIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9zdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dG=
giLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZ=
WFkIiwic3ViIjoiUnNldVlFOGpnSGVQcFdKZjFmQWI0QyIsInVzZSI6ImFjY2VzcyJ9.KPnfObr=
0uiHshPczJr-2RxrFLDdFMc0f_2SFzFcwoUBv-ZKBAsDap0d9tMbARR_e2q0UR50qj00KuQJ1oA=
JVVxJWK1gL2Kq_GmeXGwDmxy-FcODNSF3zZtOTvOSSnLGIPN-2tM_26YFd91O34soVCjfUhErdQ=
T9UTxqncBkJCV-IKzQE0MVjrRk0KVc6oiq3_FdEtk7KHPi8F3oIzXZrASeNut0HHmXrdyLYVf_i=
CCI6vaFo8f36i6arjCQ0UgzjlK5QO6kW-iRmuhCQC_RRVZB2U6tuMXvub52FDO8nr3rBojFAxe3=
dO-cPKGYMW_K11czPipYuXIt48vNtixACWQ ) this is almost certainly the major dr=
iver. Still, there is a downside to brands: probabilistic measurement is mu=
ch more difficult to verify, and you=E2=80=99re going to get better results=
 the more that you simply put money into the advertising platform=E2=80=99s=
 black box of AI driven ad placement, which inevitably means you=E2=80=99re=
 giving up both margin and knowledge of your customers in the long run.

Pinterest has had aspirations of being an ad platform a la Meta, and there =
was reason to be optimistic about their chances. What has always made Pinte=
rest compelling is that it is aspirational: you go to Pinterest to plan a w=
edding, or a home remodel, or collect recipes or craft ideas, or whatever e=
lse. This is pretty compelling data =E2=80=94 volunteered by the user in th=
e course of using the product =E2=80=94 around which to target. Plus, Pinte=
rest also has search functionality, another important signal.

Advertising, though, is a two-sided market: you not only need users and tar=
geting data, you need advertisers and ads to fill inventory; this was a str=
uggle for Pinterest even before ATT made it that much more difficult to con=
vince advertisers that your platform was worth the investment. CEO Bill Rea=
dy said on the company=E2=80=99s earnings call ( https://www.fool.com/earni=
ngs/call-transcripts/2023/04/28/pinterest-pins-q1-2023-earnings-call-transc=
ript/ ) :

The macro point in your question, which is spot-on, is that our platform =
=E2=80=94 I talked about this before, our platform overall, it=E2=80=99s a =
a more nascent ad platform. And relative to the very high consumer commerci=
al intent on our platform, we=E2=80=99re quite under-monetized. And there=
=E2=80=99s a real opportunity for us to simultaneously drive better user en=
gagement through highly relevant ads that help users satisfy commercial int=
ent while also driving up revenue on the platform. So, you=E2=80=99ve seen =
that with like our whole page optimization and the fact that we=E2=80=99re =
able to grow ad load 30%-plus while still having positive progress on engag=
ement. This demonstrates that highly relevant ads that help the user satisf=
y their intent can be great content for the user and be enhancing of both e=
ngagement and revenue simultaneously.

So, that=E2=80=99s our macro opportunity. As you rightly called out, while =
we are under-monetized overall, we are really under-monetized international=
ly. And if you look at our results, you see really positive growth on a per=
centage basis internationally for us, which is evidence that there=E2=80=99=
s a lot more potential there. And so, that=E2=80=99s something we=E2=80=99r=
e investing in directly with our first-party sales, but also something wher=
e we think partnerships can certainly be helpful in accelerating that progr=
ess.

And so, we think that overall, there=E2=80=99s a significant opportunity to=
 drive the monetization of our platform at a much greater rate than growth =
in not only users but also growth sort of engagement that we can drive mone=
tization faster than that, particularly as we=E2=80=99re demonstrating good=
 results for advertisers, particularly as they implement new measurement to=
ols, new priority safe tools. So, we feel like that is a significant opport=
unity for us and partnerships can definitely be helpful there.

In short, Pinterest has great signal, and it has headroom in terms of ad lo=
ad, but it just doesn=E2=80=99t have enough advertisers; now Amazon can fil=
l that gap by making Pinterest one of the channels available to Amazon adve=
rtisers. What is interesting is that Amazon is the inverse of Meta: whereas=
 Meta has tons of inventory and was previously able to capture signal from =
inside disparate websites and apps, Amazon has tons of products and capture=
s every conversion; the disconnect in this case will be in targeting. Remem=
ber, though, targeting is exactly what Pinterest is uniquely good at: if yo=
u must use contextual data, it=E2=80=99s hard to imagine better contextual =
data than a user=E2=80=99s Pinterest account, particularly when you layer o=
n search.

The downside for Pinterest is that this move does lower their longterm ceil=
ing as an ad business: yes, if there is ever increasing demand for Pinteres=
t native ads then the Amazon ads would be priced out, but it=E2=80=99s hard=
 to see why that would happen outside of Pinterest turning into a store in =
its own right =E2=80=94 which, Meta, of course, is trying to do right now.

